[00:00] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'We tested thousands of Kling 3.0 prompts over the past few days. This is the single prompt structure that unlocked everything. Physics, emotion, camera work, and VFX. Yeah, we\'ve actually reached the point'

[00:12] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'where we have to label videos as AI-generated. They\'re that realistic. Hi, I\'m Adil. Kling 3.0 dropped on Kickfield this week. We put out a video a few days ago breaking it down.'

[00:24] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'We\'ve been testing it non-stop since then, and I regret to inform you we barely covered 10% of what this model can actually [music] do. So, here\'s part two. Let\'s dive right in. First, let\'s talk about prompts.'

[00:37] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'In the last video, I said that short and clear prompts often give better results. And that\'s still true for simple generations. But, what we discovered is that Kling 3.0 scales incredibly well with detail. When you give it precise'

[00:50] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'instructions, it [music] actually follows them accurately. One more thing, and this is really important. No matter how good your prompt is, nothing beats a high-quality keyframe. From all our testing, strong'

[01:03] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'keyframe with a simple prompt will almost always outperform a perfect prompt with a weak image. All the keyframes in this video were generated using Kickfield Cinema Studio. I\'ll leave those images, along with a'

[01:16] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'detailed Kling 3.0 prompting guide that our prompt engineers put together, in the description below. Here we\'re looking for deep human emotions. Like she just experienced the most gut-wrenching trauma. Oh, and by the'

[01:28] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'way, right now, Kickfield is one of the only platforms outside of Kling\'s official site where you can access Kling 3.0. You also get access to Nano Banana Pro, Soul, and other top-tier AI models. And the best part, Kling 3.0 is'

[01:43] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'currently unlimited on Kickfield. So, you can experiment without burning credits. Look at that.'

[01:59] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'The acting feels very natural and very dramatic. The audio really sells it all. I like how the background sounds abruptly cut off, really intensifying the feeling.'

[02:12] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'This might be a a small detail, but it matters. For comparison, let\'s run the same prompt with Kling 2.6. &gt;&gt; [laughter] [crying]'

[02:28] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: '&gt;&gt; Yeah. You can feel the difference immediately. The lip sync, the acting, Kling 3.0 is just way ahead [music] here. At this point, comparing those two kind of feels like a a waste of [music] time. Here\'s'

[02:42] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'our key frame. I\'m looking for an F1 level pit stop. The car drives in, gets its tires changed, and [music] drives back out. Simple idea, but a detailed prompt. Here we go. Flawless execution.'

[03:02] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'The cuts are very dynamic and perfectly timed. Nothing breaks in the process. The biggest breakthrough with Kling 3.0 was timing. It truly understands when [music]'

[03:16] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'things should happen. Multishot isn\'t about more angles, it\'s about a continuous story. For this key frame, I want to combine two shots that rarely go together in real life. We\'ll start with a grip that also zooms'

[03:28] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'in. For the second scene, let\'s see the inside of the car with a man in it. And then a grip shot on the front tire followed by the camera following the car'

[03:40] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'from the side. &gt;&gt; [music] &gt;&gt; And let\'s add the man in the car as a separate element. This is a new feature available in Kling 3.0. And it\'s an absolute game changer for character consistency.'

[03:53] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Here\'s a picture of the man. We can give him a name. Let\'s go with Michael and a description. Serious man &gt;&gt; [music] &gt;&gt; loves old-school suits and cigars.'

[04:05] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Look at that.'

[04:19] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'We achieved a really nice parallax effect at the beginning. The woman turns her head very naturally as the camera zooms in. And just look at how natural it inserted Michael into the scene. &gt;&gt; [music]'

[04:31] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: '&gt;&gt; The smoke from the cigar is very realistic and the outside of the car matches with him turning the wheel, clearly indicating that he\'s &gt;&gt; [music] &gt;&gt; turning at an intersection. And the next two scenes are just perfect b-rolls. With this keyframe, I\'m hoping to test'

[04:44] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'physics adherence in sports. This has been a huge pain with every other model. Our keyframe is a guy tying his [music] shoes on the floor. I want the camera to pan and shift focus to another player I\'m dunking.'

[04:57] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'All right. He actually tied his laces, which if you tried that before with any other model,'

[05:09] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'I\'m sure you also know that was practically impossible. The most impressive part for me here is that the second player was not in the start frame. And we did not insert him as a separate element. All the credit here goes to'

[05:23] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'clean. And it\'s funny how he missed the dunk, but the ball still went in. Here [music] we have a keyframe with a POV of a driver on a racetrack. I want to see a collision during a race. One of the cars needs to flip over the'

[05:37] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'other one with a slight slow-mo. All right. There\'s a bit of morphing'

[05:49] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'happening and some of the cars in the distance disappear after the collision, but overall, the [music] scene is fantastic. The cars react naturally to the hit. The VFX and the sound effects match the'

[06:02] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'dynamics perfectly. And I really like how Clink treats lens flares. If you have an anamorphic flare in the star frame, which are those blue lines that go across the light sources,'

[06:14] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: '&gt;&gt; [music] &gt;&gt; Clink keeps them, but more importantly, adds new ones as the scene progresses. This entire scene gives off massive Michael Bay vibes. Now, let\'s test another collision, but this time from the outside of the car.'

[06:28] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'The camera is gripped [music] on top right behind the sirens. Both cars make the turn [music] and the cop car catches up and performs a PIT maneuver, which is a classic car chase technique. [music]'

[06:40] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Okay. One thing that caught my eye immediately is that the rain stops just a few'

[06:52] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'seconds into the scene. This is something that Clink still struggles with, unfortunately. But overall, we got great ground following. &gt;&gt; [music] &gt;&gt; And the PIT maneuver was executed flawlessly. Just think about how much this would'

[07:05] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'cost to recreate in real life. If one of the drivers accidentally messes up or the camera flies off, that\'s a car gone. Here, you just regenerate. With this key frame, I want to test something that\'s'

[07:17] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'practically impossible to &gt;&gt; [music] &gt;&gt; shoot in real life. A camera grip on the eagle as it\'s flying between trees. Wow, just look at how the heads stay'

[07:32] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'stable even when the eagle turns. And the eyes look in the direction he\'s about to move. It preserved the anatomy of the bird perfectly, which goes to show that it\'s not just generating pixels, it\'s [music]'

[07:45] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'rendering new worlds entirely. Shots like this are proof that AI isn\'t here to replace production, but rather create more opportunities. &gt;&gt; [music] &gt;&gt; This could be used as a really fun'

[07:57] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'b-roll, or we could even feature the eagle as the main character. With this keyframe, I\'m looking for a dynamic boxing scene. I want the camera to zoom in on the fighters, and then a POV of one of the fighters receiving a punch, followed by'

[08:11] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'a POV of the other boxer, [music] and then he goes down. Just look at that. Going back to my'

[08:24] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'point about how Clean 3.0 lens characteristics, &gt;&gt; [music] &gt;&gt; if you\'re adding bokeh around the frame, Clean 3.0 would treat it as warping of space. Clean 3.0 actually understands what it is and keeps it consistent'

[08:37] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'across all frames. I love the slight slow-mo after the punch. It really sells the impact of the hit. And the camera work [music] and sound sync perfectly. Here we have a start'

[08:49] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'frame with a skier mid-jump. I want to see if Clean 3.0 can interpret it properly and land him on the slope. I\'m not giving it much detail here. I will turn on auto multi-shot though to leave some [music] space for creativity.'

[09:03] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Uh-huh. This is the first model that nails the physics of a fall.'

[09:16] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Our skier stuck the landing, we got a nice slow-mo at the beginning, and the tracking shot in the second scene. Clean came up with that all on its own. It looks like there\'s a second skier'

[09:29] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'following him with a GoPro, and the contrast between a slow-mo and a dynamic tracking shot is just fantastic. Okay, here we have a keyframe where the guy and the car are suspended in the air.'

[09:43] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'The goal is to test the VFX combined with the camera performing an arc and then approaching the hand. Look at that. Even with so many elements'

[09:56] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'in the shot, there\'s practically no morphing. All the debris is locked in place. He reaches and grabs the handle at the last second &gt;&gt; [music] &gt;&gt; and the camera gets close at the perfect time. Really emphasizing importance of'

[10:10] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'the suspense build-up. 3D animation like this usually requires a massive budget or at least it did. Okay, here\'s a keyframe of a car mid-turn. A very dynamic shot as it is, but I want'

[10:23] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'to complicate it with a continuous camera move. The camera approaches the car from the side. The driver shifts gears and the camera goes back out. Man,'

[10:45] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'the most impressive thing here is that the camera went through the window, captured the driver, the gearshift, and then went back out and the window stayed in place. This is a very difficult shot even for'

[10:57] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'production with a huge CGI budget. And in the past, you needed start and end frames to achieve something remotely close. And the scenes wouldn\'t feel continuous and wholesome. Now we have Kling 3.0. At'

[11:09] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'this point, I\'m starting to believe that Kling 3.0 can do &gt;&gt; [music] &gt;&gt; anything. I have this keyframe of an athlete running. Let\'s get some chaos going. I want the camera to get close to the'

[11:21] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'athlete and then zoom past him and into a plane flying by. And then a few more scenes with the plane. &gt;&gt; Okay.'

[11:41] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'You know why this feels smooth? The camera movement has intention. It\'s not just moving. It feels like it knows where it\'s going. The zoom in [music] is flawless because of the focus shift from the athlete to'

[11:53] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'the plane. &gt;&gt; [music] &gt;&gt; Sound design is great, too. We got the athlete breathing heavily from the run. And notice how there\'s shadows appearing on the wing as the plane tilts. Our brain is incredibly good at spotting'

[12:07] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'when something feels fake. If any detail is even slightly off, the illusion breaks immediately. That\'s why this stuff is usually expensive and why it\'s impressive when AI gets it right.'

[12:20] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: '&gt;&gt; [music] &gt;&gt; Now, I want to see what you would make with this. Drop the opening line of a film that you wish existed. And I\'ll pick five people with the coldest line that has the potential to get nine figures in the box office and give them'

[12:32] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'a free ultimate plan. And as always, if you found this video helpful, hit the like button, subscribe, and I\'ll see you guys in the next one.'
